Breeding male.description: Blue-Gray Gnatcatchers are more widespread and less connected to desert habitats than Black-tailed. The tail on Blue-gray is almost entirely white below as seen from below, whereas the Black-tailed Gnatcatcher's is mostly black.

Male.description: The threatened California Gnatcatcher has very little range overlap with Black-tailed Gnatcatcher. Where the two co-occur, California Gnatcatchers show much less white on the underside of the tail, and have a different voice, than Black-tailed Gnatcatchers.

Adult.description: Gray Vireos are larger and chunkier, with shorter tails and thicker bills than Black-tailed Gnatcatchers.
